definition.value: Any exocrine gland whose cells bud their secretions off through the plasma membrane producing membrane-bound vesicles in the lumen; the apical portion of the secretory cell of the gland pinches off and enters the lumen; it loses part of its cytoplasm in their secretions; apocrine secretion is functional during hormonal stress or puberty; an example of true apocrine glands are mammary glands, responsible for secreting breast milk.
The functional tissue of the kidney, consisting of the nephrons.
One of the racemose glands in the walls of the esophagus that in humans are small and serve principally to lubricate the food but in some birds secrete a milky fluid on which the young are fed.
Either of the two neural nuclei within the habenula.
Four accumulations of gray substance embedded in the white substance of the cerebellum, comprising the nucleus dentatus, nucleus emboliformis, nucleus globosus, and nucleus fastigii.
System pertaining to blood vessels in the brain.
Any portion of tissue that surrounds a urethra.
A zone of skin that is part of a dorsal thoracic segment of trunk.
An artery that supplies blood to the urinary bladder.
Either the internal or external pudendal vein, running from the genital-vulvar area and abdomen and down the leg.
Vein that drains left lung and returns blood to the heart.
Vein that drains right lung and returns blood to the heart.
Any region of a nephron tubule that is straight. Examples: distal convoluted tubule, proximal convoluted tuble.
A germinal center that is located in a lymph node.

The prostatic veins form a well-marked prostatic plexus which lies partly in the fascial sheath of the prostate and partly between the sheath and the prostatic capsule. It communicates with the pudendal and vesical plexuses.

A neural nucleus that is part of the solitary tract nuclear complex. The solitary tract and nucleus are structures in the brainstem that carry and receive visceral sensation and taste from the facial (VII), glossopharyngeal (IX) and vagus (X) cranial nerves. [WP,unvetted].
An organism containing a developing embryo, fetus, or unborn offspring within the body.
The uterus in pregnancy.
A mature thymus that is entirely part of the cervical region.
A mature thymus that is entirely part of thoracic region.
A gonad prior to differentiating into a definitive testis or ovary.
The adenohypophyseal placode forms the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and gives rise to the endocrine secretory cells of the pituitary.
Rostralmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 1st branchial cleft.
Epibranchial placode between geniculate and nodose. Associated with 2nd branchial cleft.
Cranial ganglion which develops from an epibranchial placode.
An ectodermal placode that will develop into the components of the lateral line system.
Endocardium that is part of the right atrium.
A fold of tissue which extends into the peritoneal cavity of the developing embryo and participates in the separation of the pleural and peritoneal cavities.
A vein that is part of a craniocervical region.
Sum total of mesenchyme in the embryo.
Opening in the septum primum between the two atria of the embryonic heart[TMD].
A sphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.
A sphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.
Any suture between cranial and/or facial bones.
Any suture between facial bones.
The limb epidermis is the outer epithelial layer of the limb, it is a complex stratified squamous epithelium.
A nephric duct is a tube that drains a primitive kidney[GO].
A suture joining the nasal bones.
Mesenchyme that is part of a medial nasal prominence.
Mesenchyme that is part of a lateral nasal prominence.
An ectoderm that is part of a lateral nasal prominence.
A thin fold of ectoderm and endoderm that separates the pharyngeal pouches from the pharyngeal clefts in a developing embryo.
A pharyngeal membrane that separates the first pharyngeal cleft from the first pharyngeal pouch.

The superior surface of the tongue divided by the sulcus terminalis into an anterior two-thirds, the presulcal part (pars presulcalis). and a posterior one-third, the postsulcal part (pars postsulcalis).
The axilla is the area directly under the joint where the forelimb connects to the shoulder.
Mesenchyme that is part of a otic placode.
An ectoderm that is part of a buccopharyngeal membrane.
